##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node REQUIREMENTS "Requirements"

                            @{b}>> Requirements <<@{ub}

AmiGate requires:

1) Kickstart 37.175 or higher.

2) AmigaUUCP version 1.17 (1.16 will work, but generates dubious headers. See
   @{" Trouble-shooting / FAQ " link TROUBLESHOOTING} ).
   Will also work with AmiTCP/INetUtils with a bit of tweaking. See
   @{" Trouble-shooting / FAQ " link TROUBLESHOOTING}.
   
3) FidoNet editor/tosser of your choice. (@{" Spot " LINK THANKSTO} recommended for private
   usage)

4) traplist.library version 4 or higher. 

5) Last but not least, knowledge of the inner workings of both UUCP and
   FidoNet. If you are not confident with both your UUCP and FidoNet stuff
   please put AmiGate in your Trashcan and forget you ever saw it. ;-)
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node INTRODUCTION "Introduction"

                            @{b}>> Introduction <<@{ub}

After receiving a UseNet account and spending some time testing the available
news-readers and Email-readers on the scene, I found that none of these
fulfilled my needs.

Since the newly developed FidoNet editor/tosser @{" Spot " LINK THANKSTO} was able to handle
FidoNet<->UUCP gated news/mail quite nicely, I decided to use this to
read/write news/Emails.

Only thing missing was a gateway program, that fulfilled _my_ needs. So I
wrote this thingy. Hope you like it too.

Basically AmiGate will convert your UUCP news/Emails into FidoNet
netmail/echomail and the other way around. That's it.

Here's a list of some of the features, for a more detailed explanation
of the inner workings, see @{" Theory of operation " link THEORY}:

 o Public or private gating.
 o Fully FidoNet FTS/FSC compliant.
 o Direct support for DLG user.data.
 o Mailing list <-> Echomail conversion.
 o Crosspostings can be ignored (Eg. only posted to the first matching area.)
 o MIME-support (also for quoted-printable).
 o Will not post to moderated areas but instead send email to moderator.
 o FidoNet bouncing. Will inform sender if something goes wrong.
 o Optional accounting for emails.
 o Total customization of how to port the headers in UUCP messages.

Even if you don't have a FidoNet address, using it together with Spot
(a very nice FidoNet editor by Nico Francois) is much more pleasing than
using the mail and news readers available on the Amiga. (Please note that
this is my personal opinion ;-)

And I'm not the only one...

*** Area: SPOT                                    Date: 27 Jul 94  0:34:15
*** From: Nico Francois (2:292/603.10)
*** To  : Peter Lavender
*** Subj: UUCP mail version?

Check out what Peter wrote on 23 Jul 94 in a message to me:

 PL> I guess that you have prolly been asked this a million times....but is
 PL> there going to be a UUCP version of Spot? Or will that not happen due
 PL> to the way usenet newsgroups are handled?

I @{b}have@{ub} been asked this very question a lot yes :-)  And my answer is: check
out AmiGate by Brian Jacobsen (brj@boble.ping.dk), @{b}excellent@{ub} gating software!

I use Spot for e-mail and usenet newsgroups every day.  Works like a charm.

                      _o
   Nico Francois       #>    Software Engineer SCALA
   <nico@augfl.be>     4     [SPOT moderator]

... Some say it's true, And some say it's a fable
--- Spot 1.2d #1
 * Origin: -*- Spot Development -*- (2:292/603.10)
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node SETUP "Setting up AmiGate..."

                         @{b}>> Setting up AmiGate <<@{ub}

  Change the configs to your liking.

  Test the setup using some backups of your incoming UUCP mail.

  Always keep backups of your mail...

  When your setup is working you can change the UUXQT variable in
  UULIB:Config to point to a script-file that look like this instead:

  If you run AmigaUUCP by Dillon (currently maintained by Michael B. Smith)

	UUCP:C/GateMail.script
		UUCP:c/AmiGate
		UUCP:c/uuxqt

  If you use the UUXQT by Kai 'wusel' Siering, use this:

	UUCP:C/GateMail.script
		.key command/f
		.bra {
		.ket }
		getenv gating

		if WARN
			setenv gating true
			UUCP:c/AmiGate
			UUCP:c/uuxqt
			unsetenv gating
		endif

@endnode
##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node THEORY "Theory of operation"

                         @{b}>> Theory of operation <<@{ub}

  @{" FidoNet -> UUCP    " LINK FUDIAGRAM}  Gating from FidoNet to UUCP.
  @{" UUCP    -> FidoNet " LINK UFDIAGRAM}  Gating from UUCP to FidoNet.

@endnode
##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node FUDIAGRAM "Gating FidoNet to UUCP"

                         @{b}>> Gating FidoNet to UUCP <<@{ub}

                                Connected nodes
                                      
                                      |
                                      V

                                Your mailprocessor
                                tosses the mail and
                             sends it to @{" GATEADDRESS " LINK GATEADDRESS}
                               Filename: @{" FIDOTOUUCP " LINK FIDOTOUUCP}
                                      
                                      |
                                      V

                           AmiGate processes messages
                                      
                                      |
                                      V
                                                  No
                                 Listed @{" USER " LINK USER}? ------> Bounce it

                      EchoMail        |         NetMail
                      _______________/ \\________________
                      |                                |
                      V                                |
           No                                          |
Bounce it<----- Listed @{" AREA " LINK AREA}?                        |
                                                       |
                 Yes  |                                |
                      V                                |
                                   Yes Email moderator |
               NewsGroup moderated?  ----------------> |
                                                       |
                  No  |                                |
                      V                                V

                Call @{" SENDNEWS " LINK SENDNEWS}             Call @{" SENDMAIL " LINK SENDMAIL}
                Call @{" BATCHNEWS " LINK BATCHNEWS}

                      |                                |
                      \\______________   _______________/
                                     \\ /
                                      V

                               if @{" DELETEPACKET " LINK DELETEPACKET}
                            Delete the FidoNet packet


@endnode
##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node UFDIAGRAM "Gating UUCP to FidoNet"

                         @{b}>> Gating UUCP to FidoNet <<@{ub}

                                Feeding site
                                      
                                      |
                                      V
                                      
                              @{" UUSPOOLDIR " LINK UUSPOOLDIR}:X.#?
                                      
                                      |
                                      V

                                   AmiGate

                      News            |           Email
                      _______________/ \\________________
                      |                                |
                      V                                V
                                                                 No
                if compressed                     Listed @{" USER " LINK USER}? -----> Leave Mail
            call @{" UNCOMPRESSBATCH " LINK UNCOMPRESSBATCH}

                      |                                |
                      V                                V

           No                                    Convert to PKT
 Drop it <----- Listed @{" AREA " LINK AREA}?                       in @{" INBOUND " LINK INBOUND}

                      |                                |
                      V                                |
                                                       |
                Convert to PKT                         |
                 in @{" INBOUND " LINK INBOUND}                         |
                                                       |
                      |                                |
                      V                                |
                                                       |
                  if @{" RNEWS " LINK RNEWS}                          |
                 execute RNEWS                         |
              (Puts news in UUNEWS:)                   |
                                                       |
                      \\______________   _______________/
                                     \\ /
                                      V

                              Your mailprocessor
                             processes the packets

@endnode
##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node CONFIG "The configuration files:"

AmiGate will search for it's configuration files first in PROGDIR: (the
directory where AmiGate resides) and then in MAIL:.

You can always override this by starting AmiGate with a @{" CONFIGDIR " LINK CONFIGDIR}

                         @{b}>> The configuration files: <<@{ub}

   @{" AmiGate.config " LINK AMIGATECONFIG}  The configuration file
   @{" AmiGate.areas  " LINK AMIGATEAREAS }  List of areas to gate
   @{" AmiGate.users  " LINK AMIGATEUSERS }  Users file
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node AMIGATECONFIG "AmiGate.config keywords:"

                         @{b}>> AmiGate.config keywords: <<@{ub}

  @{" ACCFILE         " LINK ACCFILE}  Logfile for accounting information.
  @{" AKASITE         " LINK AKASITE}  Optional AKA UUCP site name.
  @{" AUTOAREA        " LINK AUTOAREA}  Adds U->F areas on the fly.
  @{" BATCHNEWS       " LINK BATCHNEWS}  Fully qualified name of your BatchNews executable
  @{" BLANKLINE       " LINK BLANKLINE}  Insert blank line in FidoNet messages?
  @{" CONSOLELEVEL    " LINK CONSOLELEVEL}  Consolelevel
  @{" CROSSPOST       " LINK CROSSPOST}  CrossPosting?
  @{" DELETENEWSFROMUS" LINK DELETENEWSFROMUS}  Delete news being "bounced" back?
  @{" DELETEPACKET    " LINK DELETEPACKET}  Delete FidoNet packet after processing?
  @{" DELETEUUCPMAIL  " LINK DELETEUUCPMAIL}  Delete incoming Emails after processing?
  @{" DELETEUUCPNEWS  " LINK DELETEUUCPNEWS}  Delete incoming News after processing?
  @{" DLGMODE         " LINK DLGMODE}  Check DLG user account
  @{" FAKENET         " LINK FAKENET}  If your tosser needs a fakenet address.
  @{" FIDOTOUUCP      " LINK FIDOTOUUCP}  FidoNet packetfile name.
  @{" GATEADDRESS     " LINK GATEADDRESS}  The "fake" FidoNet address of the Gate.
  @{" HEADERTEXT      " LINK HEADERTEXT}  Puts header information of your choice in UUCP messages.
  @{" INBOUND         " LINK INBOUND}  Your FidoNet inbound directory
  @{" KLUDGE          " LINK UFHEADERS}  UUCP Message headers that will be IFNA kludged.
  @{" LINEBREAK       " LINK LINEBREAK}  Break FidoNet messages to 79 characters?
  @{" LOGFILE         " LINK LOGFILE}  Name of the logfile
  @{" LOGLEVEL        " LINK LOGLEVEL}  Loglevel
  @{" MAXMSGSIZE      " LINK MAXMSGSIZE}  Maximum size of U->F messages (split at this size)
  @{" NAUGHTYREPLY    " LINK NAUGHTYREPLY}  Don't use it. Generates illegal FidoNet kludges
  @{" NEWSSERVER      " LINK NEWSSERVER}  For news to mail services.
  @{" NODEADDRESS     " LINK NODEADDRESS}  Your FidoNet address.
  @{" NOREPLYADDR     " LINK NOREPLYADDR}  Don't use the REPLYADDR kludge.
  @{" ORGANIZATION    " LINK ORGANIZATION}  Organization header of UseNet messages.
  @{" ORIGIN          " LINK ORIGIN}  FidoNet Origin line contents
  @{" PACKETAPPEND    " LINK PACKETAPPEND}  Append U->F messages to existing packets.
  @{" PORT            " LINK UFHEADERS}  UUCP Message headers that will be ported.
  @{" PUBLIC          " LINK PUBLIC}  Do you want public gating?
  @{" RNEWS           " LINK RNEWS}  Fully qualified name of RNews
  @{" SENDMAIL        " LINK SENDMAIL}  Fully qualified name of SendMail
  @{" SENDNEWS        " LINK SENDNEWS}  Fully qualified name of RNews
  @{" SITE            " LINK SITE}  Your complete UUCP site name.
  @{" STATICORIGIN    " LINK STATICORIGIN}  Always use the text from ORIGIN.
  @{" STRIP           " LINK UFHEADERS}  UUCP Message headers that will be stripped.
  @{" TEMPDIR         " LINK TEMPDIR}  Directory for temporary files.
  @{" TIMEZONE        " LINK TIMEZONE}  Timezone
  @{" UNCOMPRESSBATCH " LINK UNCOMPRESSBATCH}  Fully qualified name of UnCompressBatch
  @{" USEORIGID       " LINK USEORIGID}  German kludge for gating U->F messages.
  @{" UUSPOOLDIR      " LINK UUSPOOLDIR}  Your UUSPOOL directory.
  @{" XENOLINK        " LINK XENOLINK}  Ignore packet sender and always use INTL: kludge

@endnode
##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node ACCFILE "ACCFILE"

                          @{b}>> ACCFILE <<@{ub}

This keyword allows you to put accounting log information in a different file
than @{" LOGFILE " LINK LOGFILE}.

@{b}ACCFILE "Logs:AmiGateAcc.log"@{ub}

NOTE: You still have to set the @{" LOGLEVEL " LINK LOGLEVEL} high enough to include accounting
information.
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node AUTOAREA "AUTOAREA"

                          @{b}>> AUTOAREA <<@{ub}

AUTOAREA will cause areas not listed in the AmiGate.areas to be added
on the fly when gating from UseNet->FidoNet. Postings will be gated into
a "JUNK" area. This is similiar to the junk conference used by GRn.

You can not reply to messages gated into this area. AmiGate will refuse
them.

@{b}AUTOAREA@{ub}
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node PACKETAPPEND "PACKETAPPEND"

                          @{b}>> PACKETAPPEND <<@{ub}

PACKETAPPEND will make AmiGate append U->F messages to existing packets
your INBOUND directory.

It traverses the INBOUND directory looking for a packet which is smaller
than 100 KB. If it exists gated messages will be appended to this packet,
if not a new packet will be created.

If you use AmiGate together with AmiTCP/NNTPXfer please set this or else
you will get a PKT file for each news-file.

@{b}PACKETAPPEND@{ub}

@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node SITE "SITE"

                          @{b}>> SITE <<@{ub}

This should contain your UUCP sitename. My Email-address is
<brj@boble.ping.dk> so I set the SITE variable like this:

@{b}SITE "boble.ping.dk"@{ub}

When AmiGate traverses your @{" UUSPOOLDIR " LINK UUSPOOLDIR} looking for files, it will
only process messages bound for this site and the optional @{" AKASITE " LINK AKASITE}.
@endnode
##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node AKASITE "AKASITE"

                          @{b}>> AKASITE <<@{ub}

Optional AKASITE name. This keyword is normally not neccesary.

@{b}AKASITE "blob.ping.dk"@{ub}

When AmiGate traverses your @{" UUSPOOLDIR " LINK UUSPOOLDIR} looking for files, it will
process messages bound for this site as well as the site specified in @{" SITE " LINK SITE}.
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node TEMPDIR "TEMPDIR"

                          @{b}>> TEMPDIR <<@{ub}

When AmiGate creates temporary files, it will store them in this directory.
This will also be used when invoking @{" UNCOMPRESSBATCH " LINK UNCOMPRESSBATCH}.

If you see AmiGate run out of memory, then try changing this to your harddisk.

@{b}TEMPDIR "T:"@{ub}
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node UUSPOOLDIR "UUSPOOLDIR"

                          @{b}>> UUSPOOLDIR <<@{ub}

This is the directory AmiGate traverses when looking for incoming UUCP
Emails and News-batches. Defaults to UUSPOOL:

You may need to change this if you have subdirectories for each site in your
UUSPOOL:

@{b}UUSPOOLDIR "UUSPOOL:"@{ub}
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node HEADERTEXT "HEADERTEXT"

                          @{b}>> HEADERTEXT <<@{ub}

You can use the HEADERTEXT to put a headertext in all UUCP-messages
coming from your site.

Use at your own risk. Potentionally dangerous, since you can use this
to create headers that are non-RFC conforming.

Under normal circumstances there is no need to use HEADERTEXT.

It accepts some limited format specifiers:

 %n inserts the users email-address (without sitename appended).
 %N inserts the users real name.
 %s inserts your SITENAME.
 %% inserts a % character.
 \\n inserts a newline character.

It is for instance useful to generate a different Reply-To: header.

NOTE: If you use it to generate a different Reply-To: header you should
      use @{b}HEADERTEXT "Reply-To: %n@%s (%N)"@{ub} otherwise it won't conform
      with the RFC's.

@{b}HEADERTEXT "Reply-To: %n@%s (%N)\\nX-CrazyHeader: Afternoons and coffeespoons"@{ub}
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node FIDOTOUUCP "FIDOTOUUCP"

                          @{b}>> FIDOTOUUCP <<@{ub}

This is the name of the FidoNet packet, in which AmiGate will look for F->U
messages.

If your tosser creates a packet named: 2.999.99.0.OUT you would set this to:

@{b}FIDOTOUUCP "Mail:OutBound/2.999.99.0.OUT"@{ub}

You can override this via the @{" GATEPKT " LINK GATEPKT} argument.
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node DELETENEWSFROMUS "DELETENEWSFROMUS"

                          @{b}>> DELETENEWSFROMUS <<@{ub}

When using a news to mail gateway, you might get your news postings tossed
back at you. If you specify:

@{b}DELETENEWSFROMUS@{ub}

AmiGate will ignore news from your feed that has a user on your SITE as a
sender. 

Under normal circumstances you won't need this.
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node DELETEPACKET "DELETEPACKET"

                          @{b}>> DELETEPACKET <<@{ub}

If this keyword is specified, AmiGate will delete the FidoNet packet
@{" FIDOTOUUCP " LINK FIDOTOUUCP} after processing.

While setting up AmiGate you may choose to comment out this keyword, so the
packet won't be deleted after processing.

If anything goes wrong during gating, the packet will NOT be deleted.

@{b}DELETEPACKET@{ub}
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node NEWSSERVER "NEWSSERVER"

                          @{b}>> NEWSSERVER <<@{ub}

If you are using a servide that won't allow you to post news as news (like
demon in the UK) you can use this option in conjunction with the "N" option
in the areas setting to have the news posted from your site gated into an
email with the name of this server appended.

An example:

You have NEWSSERVER set to:

@{b}NEWSSERVER "news.demon.co.uk"@{ub}

And in your AmiGate.areas:

@{b}AREA N alt.fan.jello-biafra AF.JELLO@{ub}

Messages written in the AF.JELLO FidoNet echo will be sent as email to:

<alt.fan.jello-biafra@news.demon.co.uk>

See also @{" AREA " LINK AREA}
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node NODEADDRESS "NODEADDRESS"

                          @{b}>> NODEADDRESS <<@{ub}

This should be set to your FidoNet address. So if your FidoNet address
is "2:236/19.0" set this to:

@{b}NODEADDRESS "2:236/19.0"@{ub}

If you are a point and only run AmiGate to be able to use your FidoNet
editor for reading and writing News/Emails, you probably want to set
this to a point-address.
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node NOREPLYADDR "NOREPLYADDR"

                          @{b}>> NOREPLYADDR <<@{ub}

Some BBS software/FidoNet editors do not support the REPLYADDR kludge as
described in FSC-0035.
If you specify

@{b}NOREPLYADDR@{ub}

AmiGate will try to put the email address of the sender into the FidoNet
To: field instead of the real name. If the email-address is longer than
the 36 characters allowed in the FidoNet To: field, it will use the
REPLYADDR kludge anyway.

Don't use it if you don't need it.
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node FAKENET "FAKENET"

                          @{b}>> FAKENET <<@{ub}

If your tosser needs a fakenet SEEN-BY on FidoNet Echomail messages
then specify your fakenet here:

@{b}FAKENET "1019"@{ub}

@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node GATEADDRESS "GATEADDRESS"

                          @{b}>> GATEADDRESS <<@{ub}

Set this to the "fake" FidoNet address assigned to the gate.

If you set up the gate as "2:236/19.1":

@{b}GATEADDRESS "2:236/19.1"@{ub}

Your tosser should toss U->F messages to this address.
If you are running a node this will usually be a point address.
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node ORIGIN "ORIGIN"

                          @{b}>> ORIGIN <<@{ub}

When gating UUCP news to a FidoNet area, then under normal circumstances
the Origin line will be set to the Organization header.

For messages without an Organization header, the contents of this
setting will be used:

@{b}ORIGIN "Boblebadet"@{ub}

If you always want to use this text then specify @{" STATICORIGIN " LINK STATICORIGIN} as well.

@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node STATICORIGIN "STATICORIGIN"

                          @{b}>> STATICORIGIN <<@{ub}

When gating UUCP news to a FidoNet area, then under normal circumstances
the Origin line will be set to the Organization header.

This switch will cause AmiGate to always use the text from @{" ORIGIN " LINK ORIGIN}.

@{b}STATICORIGIN@{ub}
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node ORGANIZATION "ORGANIZATION"

                          @{b}>> ORGANIZATION <<@{ub}

This will be put into the Organization: header for all messages coming
from AmiGate when gating FidoNet to UUCP.

@{b}ORGANIZATION "Boblebadet, Copenhagen, Denmark"@{ub}
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node CROSSPOST "CROSSPOST"

                          @{b}>> CROSSPOST <<@{ub}

If you are running a public gate, you should specify

@{b}CROSSPOST@{ub}

Comment out this line and crossposted messages will only be gated to the first
matching FidoNet area (very useful is you run a private site and don't want to
look at all these MB crossposts).
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node LINEBREAK "LINEBREAK"

                          @{b}>> LINEBREAK <<@{ub}

The following is to support STUPID UseNet news readers
which cannot figure out how to break lines that are too long.

LINEBREAK will cause an EXPLICIT line break to be inserted into
any line which is longer than 80 characters. This slows down F->U gating
a bit.

@{b}LINEBREAK@{ub}
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node INBOUND "INBOUND"

                          @{b}>> INBOUND <<@{ub}

Set this to your FidoNet inbound directory. AmiGate will place its
FidoNet packets there.

@{b}INBOUND "Mail:Inbound"@{ub}
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node TIMEZONE "TIMEZONE"

                          @{b}>> TIMEZONE <<@{ub}

Set this to the TimeZone of your country. Set it to the same as your
UULIB:Config TimeZone setting.

@{b}TIMEZONE "CET"@{ub}
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node BATCHNEWS "BATCHNEWS"

                          @{b}>> BATCHNEWS <<@{ub}

If BATCHNEWS is specified, AmiGate will invoke BATCHNEWS after gating
the echomail messages for UseNet conferences.

Comment it out, if you want manual processing.

@{b}BATCHNEWS "uucp:c/batchnews"@{ub}
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node RNEWS "RNEWS"

                          @{b}>> RNEWS <<@{ub}

If RNEWS is specified, AmiGate will invoke Rnews after gating
the messages in a UUCP newsbatch to FidoNet.

The advantage of getting AmiGate to invoke Rnews instead of letting
UUXQT handle this is that the News-batch won't have to be decompressed
twice.

Comment it out, if you want manual processing.

@{b}RNEWS "uucp:c/rnews -h -t T:"@{ub}
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node SENDNEWS "SENDNEWS"

                          @{b}>> SENDNEWS <<@{ub}

AmiGate will use RNews when gating FidoNet echomail to a UseNet conference.

Where to find it:

@{b}SENDNEWS "uucp:c/rnews -h -p -t T:"@{ub}
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node SENDMAIL "SENDMAIL"

                          @{b}>> SENDMAIL <<@{ub}

AmiGate will use SendMail when gating FidoNet netmail to a UUCP Emails.

Use

@{b}SENDMAIL "uucp:c/sendmail -R \\"\\" <"@{ub}

for AmigaUUCP 1.17
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node UNCOMPRESSBATCH "UNCOMPRESSBATCH"

                          @{b}>> UNCOMPRESSBATCH <<@{ub}

Fully qualified name of your UnCompressBatch executable.

@{b}UNCOMPRESSBATCH "uucp:c/uncompressbatch"@{ub}

Please note that the current version of UnCompressBatch does ONLY handle
compressed News. If you are receiving News that are GZip'ed or LhA'ed,
you'll need to dearchive them manually before starting AmiGate.

NOTE: A version of UnCompressBatch that support GZip'ed news is available
      from me.
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node DELETEUUCPMAIL "DELETEUUCPMAIL"

                          @{b}>> DELETEUUCPMAIL <<@{ub}

Do you want AmiGate to delete succesfully gated Emails from UUSPOOL: after
processing then specify:

@{b}DELETEUUCPMAIL@{ub}

Comment out this line if you want to keep them for manual processing.

NOTE: AmiGate will never delete undelivered mail. So if you have set up BMS
      on your system, don't worry. AmiGate will not delete these.
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node DELETEUUCPNEWS "DELETEUUCPNEWS"

                          @{b}>> DELETEUUCPNEWS <<@{ub}

Do you want AmiGate to delete succesfully gated news from UUSPOOL: after
processing then specify:

@{b}DELETEUUCPNEWS@{ub}

Comment out this line if you want to keep them for manual processing.

NOTE: If you have specified @{" RNEWS " LINK RNEWS} then the news files will
      always be deleted, so this only makes sense, if RNEWS is left out.
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node NAUGHTYREPLY "NAUGHTYREPLY"

                          @{b}>> NAUGHTYREPLY <<@{ub}

Normally AmiGate generates FidoNet MSGID kludges that look like this:

^MSGID: 2:999/99.0 E5CD71A1

If you specify:

@{b}NAUGHTYREPLY@{ub}

AmiGate will generate header and kludges differently:

1) UseNet->FidoNet: "Message-ID:" header will be translated to "^MSGID:" kludge
2) FidoNet->UseNet: "^REPLY:" kludge will be translated to "References:" header
                    for news and "In-Reply-To:" for Emails.

@{b}This breaks just about every law there is in FidoNet. Don't use it, if you're
gating for anybody else but yourself. Don't say I didn't warn you.@{ub}

On the other hand, this will cause thread reading to be available on the UseNet
side and Spot for instance is able to handle these illegal kludges.
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node USEORIGID "USEORIGID"

                          @{b}>> USEORIGID <<@{ub}

If you specify:

@{b}USEORIGID@{ub}

AmiGate will translate:

1) UseNet->FidoNet: "Message-ID:" header will be translated to "^ORIGID:" kludge

2) FidoNet->UseNet: "^ORIGID" kludge will be translated to "Message-ID:" header

This is a german extension to the FSC (FidoNet proposals). Don't use it if you
don't need it.
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node LOGFILE "LOGFILE"

                          @{b}>> LOGFILE <<@{ub}

The file AmiGate will use for logging:

@{b}LOGFILE "Logs:AmiGate.log"@{ub}

All messages from AmiGate will be logged in this file.

This is what the logfile may look like:

! 16-Feb-94 21:18:13  AmiGate 1.2c started
! 16-Feb-94 21:18:13  U->F: Email from "kleis@mink.ping.dk" sent to "Brian Jacobsen"
$ 16-Feb-94 21:18:13  U->F: # 2:999/99.9 # 1194 # kleis@mink.ping.dk
| 16-Feb-94 21:18:20  U->F: 23 Msgs, 1 NetMail, 22 EchoMail.
| 16-Feb-94 21:18:20  F->U: 0 Msgs, 0 NetMail, 0 EchoMail.
! 16-Feb-94 21:18:20  AmiGate 1.2c ended

You can adjust the amount of information in the logfile by setting the
@{" LOGLEVEL " LINK LOGLEVEL}.
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node LOGLEVEL "LOGLEVEL"

                          @{b}>> LOGLEVEL <<@{ub}

This allows you to specify how much info you want in your @{" LOGFILE " LINK LOGFILE}.

The levels are:

0 Error                  LogChar "+" 
1 Warnings               LogChar "-"
2 General info           LogChar "|" 
3 Detailed info          LogChar "!"
4 Accounting             LogChar "$"
5 General debug          LogChar "#" 
6 Detailed debug         LogChar "*"

@{b}LOGLEVEL 4@{ub}
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node CONSOLELEVEL "CONSOLELEVEL"

                          @{b}>> CONSOLELEVEL <<@{ub}

This allows you to specify how much info AmiGate will output to the console.

See @{" LOGLEVEL " LINK LOGLEVEL} for a description of the levels.

@{b}CONSOLELEVEL 6@{ub}
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node MAXMSGSIZE "MAXMSGSIZE"

                          @{b}>> MAXMSGSIZE <<@{ub}

This allows you to specify the maximum size (bytes) of messages that will be gated.

This only applies to U->F gating.

Only the size of the message text is measured, so set it a few hundred bytes
lower to account for the message header and trailer.

Messages that exceeds this size will be split.

If you comment out this keyword or set it to 0 no size splitting will be done.

To prevent you from doing something stupid ;-) values lower than 1000 will be
ignored.

@{b}MAXMSGSIZE 10240@{ub}
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node PUBLIC "PUBLIC"

                          @{b}>> PUBLIC <<@{ub}

AmiGate will normally only gate from users listed in @{" AmiGate.users " LINK AMIGATEUSERS}.

But AmiGate can be configured to be a public gate if you like.
 
Specify PUBLIC and the type.

0 This is the same as leaving out the PUBLIC keyword.
  AmiGate will only gate to and from users in the AmiGate.users file.

1 Public gating with FTN style addressing for both news and emails.
  AmiGate will the search the AmiGate.users file before falling back to FTN
  style adressing.

2 Same as no. 1 but Fidonet users not listed in the AmiGate.users file will
  only be allowed to send news (no emails).

3 Public gating with site style addressing for both news and emails.
  AmiGate will the search the AmiGate.users file before falling back to site
  style adressing.


@{b}PUBLIC 0@{ub}

Example:

If the PUBLIC keyword is set to 1 and a FidoNet user called "Brian Jacobsen"
at 2:236/19.73 writes an email to the gate and he's not listed then his
email-address will become:

<Brian.Jacobsen@p73.f19.n236.z2.fidonet.org>

If the PUBLIC keyword is set to 3 and a FidoNet user called "Brian Jacobsen"
at 2:236/19.73 writes an email to the gate and he's not listed then his
email-address will become:

<Brian.Jacobsen@p73.f19.n236.z2.boble.ping.dk>

@endnode
##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node DLGMODE "DLGMODE"

                          @{b}>> DLGMODE <<@{ub}

When determining whether a user is allowed to use the gate AmiGate normally
only searches the AmiGate.users file.

Specifying DLGMODE causes AmiGate to also check the UUCP flag in
USER:uucpname/User.Data as used by DLG.

If the UUCP flag is set to 2 then the user will be allowed to post.

Here is the flow-chart:

                        @{b}>> FidoNet->UUCP <<@{ub}

- Check the fido address, if NOT equal to the NODEADDRESS then proceed as now.

- If the address is the NODEADDRESS then the msg was written from the BBS
  so check user bbs access:
  - compute uucpname by replacing all space in the [From] field by a '_'
    (Example: A msg is from "Brian Jacobsen", uucpname ='Brian_Jacobsen')
    - if user:uucpname/User.Data exists     /* where to get access flag */
      - if UUCP flag is set /* then user has access */
         - The user is allowed to write.
  - if any of the above fail user does not have write access, bounce msg.

                        @{b}>> UUCP->FidoNet <<@{ub}

- Check if uucpname is found in amigate.users, if yes proceed as now

- If uucpname is not found, then it might be for a bbs user so check access
  flag datas by checking UUCP flag of user:uucpname/User.Data as above.

- If this check fail or if user:uucpname/User.Data does not exist then the user
  does not have uucp access so do not transmit. if check is successful then
  compute realname by replacing '_' by space and transmit to the NODEADDRESS.
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node BLANKLINE "BLANKLINE"

                          @{b}>> BLANKLINE <<@{ub}

If you want a blank line in FidoNet messages after kludges but before the
message text
+ a blank IFNA ^A kludge between "true" FidoNet kludges and KLUDGED
UUCP headers specify:

@{b}BLANKLINE@{ub}
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node NOQP "NOQP"

                          @{b}>> NOQP <<@{ub}

Under normal circumstances AmiGate will send emails containing 8-bit charsets
in MIME quoted-printable as the transportation layer of UUCP only guarantee
preservation of 7 bits.

This can be annoying for the user in the other end if his mail-reader does not
support MIME.

Therefore you can override this in two ways, first as a command-line switch
in which case AmiGate will never send MIME quoted-printable.

  1> @{b}AmiGate NOQP@{ub}

Or second, you can specify NOQP in () after the To: user line when writing the
To: user address in your Fidonet-editor.

To: kleis@mink.ping.dk(NOQP)

This will only override it for this email.
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node XENOLINK "XENOLINK"

                          @{b}>> XENOLINK <<@{ub}

Under normal circumstances AmiGate checks that the FidoNet packet to be
gated is actually coming from your @{" NODEADDRESS " LINK NODEADDRESS}.

And it will only put an INTL: kludge if the FidoNet zone destination of a
netmail differs from your own zone.

@{b}XENOLINK@{ub}

will cause AmiGate to ignore who sent the packet (packetheader sender)
and always put INTL: kludges on netmails.

Only use this switch if you have to.
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node UFHEADERS "PORT, STRIP, KLUDGE"

                          @{b}>> PORT, STRIP, KLUDGE <<@{ub}

A special feature of AmiGate is the ability to specify exactly how you want
UseNet headers converted when gating to FidoNet.

@{b}PORT@{ub}

The header will be ported directly to FidoNet and become part of the message
text.

@{b}STRIP@{ub}

The header will be stripped from the FidoNet message.

@{b}KLUDGE@{ub}

The header will be ported to FidoNet but hidden with an IFNA kludge (^A).

In general, if you're running a public gate, then you'd probably want STRIP
as the default.

Perhaps the best way to show how this works is with an example. I received
the following Email:

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
From mink.ping.dk!kleis Wed Dec 15 21:59:01 1993
Received: from mink by ic1.ic.dk with UUCP id AA15015
  (5.65c8/IDA-1.4.4j); Wed, 15 Dec 1993 21:53:20 +0100
Received: by mink.ping.dk (V1.16/wusel)
	  id <0jgu@mink.ping.dk>; Wed, 15 Dec 93 21:19:52 CET
Date: Wed, 15 Dec 93 21:19:52 CET
Message-Id: <9312152019.0jgt@mink.ping.dk>
From: kleis@mink.ping.dk (Klaus Alexander Seistrup)
To: brj@boble.ping.dk
Subject: Test
X-Charset: ISO_8859-1
X-Char-Esc: 29

Test.......................................

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------



Assuming my AmiGate.config looks like this:
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
; First specify the default:
STRIP
;
; Now specify exceptions to the default:
;
PORT "Received:"
PORT "Subject:"
KLUDGE "X-Charset:"
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------



Then the FidoNet message will look like this:
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
XPkt v1.0 - Examine FidoNet *.PKT-files.
©1992 Fredrik Kjellberg 2:203/416@FidoNet

- PKTHEADER -----------------------------------------------------------------
Header type: FSC-0039
Orig adr   : 2:999/99.0
Dest adr   : 2:999/99.9
Created    : 1994-02-21 20:14:19
Prod Code  : feh - UNKNOWN
PVMajor    : 0
PVMinor    : 0
Password   :
Capability : 0001h
ProdData   : 00000000h

- MSG    1 ------------------------------------------------------------------
Orig/Dest: 999/99 -> 999/99
Attr     : PVT
From     : Klaus Alexander Seistrup                 Date: 15 Dec 93  21:19:52
To       : Brian Jacobsen
Subj     : Test

^TOPT 9
^MSGID: 2:999/99.0 E5CD71A1
^REPLYADDR kleis@mink.ping.dk
^PID: AmiGate 0.16 (19.2.94)
Received: from mink by ic1.ic.dk with UUCP id AA15015
  (5.65c8/IDA-1.4.4j); Wed, 15 Dec 1993 21:53:20 +0100
Received: by mink.ping.dk (V1.16/wusel)
	  id <0jgu@mink.ping.dk>; Wed, 15 Dec 93 21:19:52 CET
Subject: Test
^X-Charset: ISO_8859-1

Test.............................................


- INFO ----------------------------------------------------------------------
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node AMIGATEUSERS "AmiGate.users keywords:"

                         @{b}>> AmiGate.users keywords: <<@{ub}

AmiGate.users should contain one or more of the following:

  @{" USER " LINK USER}  A user that will be allowed to send and receive mail through the gate.
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node USER "USER"

                          @{b}>> USER <<@{ub}

This keyword is used to describe a user that will be allowed to use the gate.
To send/receive mail (both netmail and echomail) a user must be either be
listed in this or AmiGate must have been set up to do @{" PUBLIC " LINK PUBLIC} gating.

The syntax is:

@{b}USER <UUCP-name> <FidoNet-address> <real name (Fido-Name)>@{ub}

Examples:

USER brj		2:999/99.9 Brian Jacobsen
USER postmaster		2:999/99.9 PostMester
USER hannibal		2:111/11.1 Hannibal the Cannibal
USER aminetw		2:999/99.9 AmiNet weekly
USER aminetd		2:999/99.9 AmiNet daily


Please note that AmiGate checks both the FidoNet address and the Real Name
when checking if a user is allowed to post.

If you have the same <UUCP-name> listed more than once, U->F emails will
only be sent to the first listed address.
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node AMIGATEAREAS "AmiGate.areas keywords:"

                         @{b}>> AmiGate.areas keywords: <<@{ub}

AmiGate.areas should contain one or more of the following keywords:

  @{" AREA       " LINK AREA}  Description of UseNet conference <-> FidoNet area.
  @{" MAILLIST   " LINK MAILLIST}  Description of UseNet mailinglist <-> FidoNet area.
  @{" NEWSACTIVE " LINK NEWSACTIVE}  Read areas from an active file.

@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node AREA "AREA"

                          @{b}>> AREA <<@{ub}

This keyword describes a normally gated area. Eg. a UseNet conference that
will be gated into a FidoNet echomail area.

The syntax is:

@{b}AREA MapCode <UseNet-name> <FidoNet-areaname> <moderator>@{ub}

Where MapCode is one of the following:

   + Gate Both ways
   - Don't gate F->U
   M Moderated. Postings will be converted to an Email to <moderator>
   N Send all news to <UseNet-name>@@{"NEWSSERVER" LINK NEWSSERVER} as Emails.

<UseNet-name> is the name of the UseNet conference.
<FidoNet-areaname> is the name of the FidoNet area.
<moderator> is only relevant for moderated areas of course.

Examples:

AREA + comp.sys.amiga.programmer      CSA.PROGRAMMER
AREA - comp.sources.amiga             COMP.SRC.AMIGA
AREA M comp.sys.amiga.announce        CSA.ANNOUNCE     announce@cs.ucdavis.edu
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node MAILLIST "MAILLIST"

                          @{b}>> MAILLIST <<@{ub}

This special feature makes it possible to gate a mailing-list into a FidoNet
area.

The syntax is:

@{b}MAILLIST MapCode <FidoNet-areaname> <username> <mailinglistname>@{ub}

Where MapCode is one of the following:

   +  Gate Both ways @{b}(*)@{ub}.
   -  Don't gate F->U.
   ++ Gate Both ways @{b}(*)@{ub}. Do not check To: and Cc: header
   -- Don't gate F->U. Do not check To: and Cc: header

<FidoNet-areaname> is the name of the FidoNet area.
<username>         must be the user you used when subscribing to the
                   mailing-list. This user should also be listed in
                   your @{" AmiGate.users " LINK AMIGATEUSERS} file.
<mailinglistname>  is the address of the mailing-list.
                   AmiGate will search the To: and Cc: for this address
                   except when using ++ or -- MapCode.

If using the ++ or -- switch then @{b}THIS USER MUST BE UNIQUE@{ub} and @{b}ONLY USED
FOR THE MAILINGLIST@{ub} because all emails to this user will end up in the
FidoNet area.

@{b}(*)@{ub} All messages to the mailing-list will appear to be coming from <username>
    Be sure the mailing-list keeper accepts this before setting it to gate
    both ways.

Examples:

MAILLIST -- AMINET.WEEKLY aminetw aminet-weekly@wunet.wustl.edu
MAILLIST -- AMINET.DAILY  aminetd aminet-daily@wunet.wustl.edu
MAILLIST - MINK.FILES    brj     minknews@mink.ping.dk
MAILLIST + FUGATEWAYS    brj     fuuf@aldhfn.org
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node NEWSACTIVE "NEWSACTIVE"

                          @{b}>> NEWSACTIVE <<@{ub}


If you have a list of active newsgroups like the one required by GRn or
AmiTCP, you can use this to save you from having to type in the areas
here. Place this keyword after your AREA definitions in this config, as
the AREA will then be read and added first allowing you to override the
settings created from the NEWSACTIVE keyword.

The active file is usually in the format:
   news.group.name ....

AmiGate will ignore everything after the newsgroup name and create the
area as if had been created with

   AREA + news.group.name news.group.name


@{b}NEWSACTIVE "UULIB:NewsGroups"@{ub}
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node CLIARGS "Command line arguments:"

                         @{b}>> The configuration files: <<@{ub}

   @{" CONFIGDIR   " LINK CONFIGDIR}  Overrides the default directory for the configuration files
   @{" DUMPCONFIG  " LINK DUMPCONFIG}  A complete list of the config
   @{" GATEPKT     " LINK GATEPKT}  Gate a single FidoNet packet
   @{" GATENEWS    " LINK GATENEWS}  Gate a single Usenet newsfile
   @{" GATEMAILBOX " LINK GATEMAILBOX}  Gate emails from a Mailbox instead of UUSPOOL:
   @{" NOQP        " LINK NOQP}  Don't use MIME quoted-printable
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node CONFIGDIR "CONFIGDIR"

                          @{b}>> CONFIGDIR <<@{ub}

AmiGate will search for it's configuration files first in PROGDIR: (the
directory where AmiGate resides) and then in MAIL:.

You can override this by starting AmiGate with a CONFIGDIR argument.

Example:

  1> @{b}AmiGate CONFIGDIR SYS:Configs@{ub}

@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node DUMPCONFIG "DUMPCONFIG"

                          @{b}>> DUMPCONFIG <<@{ub}

Dumps the configuration. You better have a scrollbar on your CLI. :)

Can be useful for finding errors in your configuration files.

Example:

  1> @{b}AmiGate DUMPCONFIG@{ub}

@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node GATEPKT "GATEPKT"

                          @{b}>> GATEPKT <<@{ub}

If your mailer software don't support not packing packets then
use AmiGate as the archiver.

Example:

  1> @{b}AmiGate GATEPKT dummyargument packet@{ub}
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node GATENEWS "GATENEWS"

                          @{b}>> GATENEWS <<@{ub}

Gates a single Usenet newsfile to FidoNet echomail.

Example:

  1> @{b}AmiGate GATENEWS logs:bax/D.pingnetd0bbpww@{ub}
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node GATEMAILBOX "GATEMAILBOX"

                          @{b}>> GATEMAILBOX <<@{ub}

Gates emails from a MailBox instead of UUSPOOL.

Example:

  1> @{b}AmiGate GATEMAILBOX UUMail:brj@{ub}

If @{" DELETEUUCPMAIL " LINK DELETEUUCPMAIL} is specified then the file will be deleted
if processed succesfully.
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node TROUBLESHOOTING "Troubleshooting / Frequently asked questions"

                         @{b}>> Troubleshooting / FAQ <<@{ub}

@{" Question  1 " LINK Q1}  How does the builtin charset conversion routines work?

@{" Question  2 " LINK Q2}  AmiGate says "U->F: !rnews out of sync" when trying to
               process UUCP newsbatches.

@{" Question  3 " LINK Q3}  AmiGate does not work with my XFH partitions.
               I get the error: 209: packet request type unknown.

@{" Question  4 " LINK Q4}  Does Amigate call UUxqt when it has finished the
               gating part? The fact that UUSPOOL: is empty suggests this.

@{" Question  5 " LINK Q5}  How do I write netmails to the gate?

@{" Question  6 " LINK Q6}  My tosser won't allow me to specify the name of my
               outbound packet. It wants an archiver.

@{" Question  7 " LINK Q7}  AmiGate rejects mail written by one of my users. I'm
               quite sure he is listed?

@{" Question  8 " LINK Q8}  When gating from FidoNet to UseNet the messages have
               two Message-ID headers?

@{" Question  9 " LINK Q8}  When gating from FidoNet to UseNet the From: header
               contains an extra pair of () after my name?

@{" Question 10 " LINK Q10}  I receive news compressed with GZip but my "uncompressbatch"
               is only able to handle compressed news.

@{" Question 11 " LINK Q11}  How come my news postings does not have a proper "References"
               header? or Some jerk complains he is unable to do thread
               reading on my postings?

@{" Question 12 " LINK Q12}  Will AmiGate work with AmiTCP?

@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node Q1 "Troubleshooting / Frequently asked questions"

Good question, as this can seem rather complicated.

                      @{b}FidoNet Netmail -> UUCP email:@{ub}

First AmiGate checks if the message contains any hibit characters.
If this is not the case then the message will just be sent as is.

If it contained hi-bit chars then check for a valid CHRS: kludge in the
FidoNet message:

If the kludge is @{b}CHRS: LATIN-1 2@{ub} then send as MIME Quoted-Printable.

If the kludge is @{b}CHRS: IBMPC 2@{ub} then convert to ISO-8859 charset and send as
MIME Quoted-Printable.

If no valid CHRS: kludge is found and the message contained hi-bit chars then
these will be stripped.

As you see AmiGate will normally never send 8-bit emails due to the fact
that there is a rather large chance that this will be stripped underway
by some machine. This can be overridden by using the @{" NOQP " LINK NOQP} command line
switch.

                  @{b}FidoNet Echomail -> UseNet newsgroups:@{ub}

Same as above except that the 8-bit messages will be sent with standard MIME

'Content-Type: text/plain; charset=iso-8859-1'
'Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit'

headers rather than Quoted-Printable.

                          @{b}UUCP -> FidoNet:@{ub}

Nowhere near as complicated. Quoted-Printable will be converted to ISO-8859.
ISO-8859 messages will receive a @{b}CHRS: LATIN-1 2@{ub}.

So tell all your users that if they want to preserve bit 8, they should
switch to a FidoNet editor that supports charsets. If they do, then
AmiGate will put a nice MIME-header in the UUCP-messages.

If you don't understand a word I said, never mind. Rest assured AmiGate will
do whatever is possible to ensure correct charset conversion.
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node Q2 "Troubleshooting / Frequently asked questions"

The logic is as follows:

Read First line
If "#! cunbatch"
   Call uncompressbatch

If "#! rnews ..."
   Okay multiple article newsfile
else
   Okay this is single article newsfile

The number following the "#! rnews" sentence indicates the number of bytes to
process as a news article. After having read that number of bytes AmiGate
tries to read the next line. That line is expected to be a new "#! rnews"
line. If it's not AmiGate determines that the bundle is corrupted and gives
you the "!rnews out of synch" error message.

The files in question will be renamed from X.yyyyyyyy and D.zzzzzzzz to
E.yyyyyyyy and E.yyyyyyyy.

@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node Q3 "Troubleshooting / Frequently asked questions"

Get the author of XFH to support ExamineFH(). Don't blame me ;-)

@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node Q4 "Troubleshooting / Frequently asked questions"

No, it doesn't. It will feed the news to "Rnews" if you specified this in
AmiGate.config, but it will not touch the Emails. Unless you specified
@{" DELETEUUCPMAIL " LINK DELETEUUCPMAIL}, in which case succesfully gated Emails will be deleted
after processing.

If you still find your UUSPOOL: empty, then chances are that you're running
'wusel' UUCP. My best advice is: Don't. The second best is to use the script
described under @{" SETUP " LINK SETUP}.

@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node Q5 "Troubleshooting / Frequently asked questions"

Either the FidoNet To: field or the first line in the letter must contain
a valid Email-address. AmiGate also accepts additional lines containing
Cc: or Bcc:.

Okay, an example. I want to send an Email to dummy1@amigate.org with
carbon-copies to dummy2@amigate.org and dummy3@amigate.org:

So I write a netmail that looks like this:

From: Brian Jacobsen		2:999/99.9
To: AmiGate			2:999/99.0
Subject: This is a test

------------------------ Body text -------------------------
To: dummy1@amigate.org
Cc: dummy2@amigate.org, dummy3@amigate.org

Hey, I was walking my bag through a twenty-storey nonstop snowstorm
Pirrelli calendar girls wrestling in body lotion.
My head is swimming with poetry and prosa
Excuse me one moment, whilst I powder my nose.

Kind regards
Brian
-------------------- End of body text ----------------------
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------

@node Q6 "Troubleshooting / Frequently asked questions"

> If I write messages to the gated newsgroups I don't really have control
> over what the resulting exported file will be called. How then can I
> inform Amigate of the correct filename to gate from Fido - uucp.

> 2.999.99.1.FLO     73 ----rwed Today     12:06:00: From 2:999/99@fidonet;
> 2.999.99.1.SA0    295 ----rwed Today     12:06:00

Set up AmiGate as the archiver for point 1 in your tosser. If you have say
"C:Lha a" today you should be able to use "AmiGate @{" GATEPKT " LINK GATEPKT}" instead.
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node Q7 "Troubleshooting / Frequently asked questions"

I'm quite sure he is not. ;-)

Let's take some common cases. You have this @{" USER " LINK USER} in your
AmiGate.config.

@{b}USER brj                2:999/99.9     Brian Jacobsen@{ub}


1. He complains that he gets the following message from the gate:
      The user "Prowler" (2:999/99.9) is not allowed to use the gate.

Yes, he's changed the FidoNet from: to "Prowler" when writing the letter.
Since AmiGate double checks the address AND the name, this will be rejected.
Tell him always to use his real name: Brian Jacobsen

2. He complains that he gets the following message from the gate:
      The user "Brian Jacobsen" (2:999/99.8) is not allowed to use the gate.

Same thing, but this time you have set his address wrong. .8 should be .9
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node Q8 "Troubleshooting / Frequently asked questions"

You're using AmigaUUCP version 1.16 or older.

Upgrading to AmigaUUCP 1.17b4 or higher will fix it.

All binaries, sources, and man pages for 1.17b4 are available for BMS from
adastra.cvl.va.us and by FTP from wade1.ab.umd.edu:/uucp

@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node Q10 "Troubleshooting / Frequently asked questions"

AmigaUUCP 1.17b5 will include "uncompressbatch" with external archiver
support. (I know, 'cause I added it ;-)

Until then you can get the "uncompressbatch" version from me.

Just send me an email.
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node Q11 "Troubleshooting / Frequently asked questions"

 > BTW what is a References: line? I have one asshole in a newsgroup
 > complaining that I'm not posting with one. What is it and should I give
 > a damn? BTW MessageID threading doesn't seem to work. Is that
 > unavoidable or could this be added to Amigate?

FidoNet message-threading and the UseNet equivalent does not work well
together. But if you are using AmiGate together with Spot for a single user
system you can get the reply-threading somewhat functional by using the
@{" NAUGHTYREPLY " LINK NAUGHTYREPLY} switch in the config. This will hack the usenet Message-ID
into the FidoNet MSGID kludge and AmiGate will know and use this when you
reply to a message.

However the @{" NAUGHTYREPLY " LINK NAUGHTYREPLY} switch is only recommended for a private gate
setup together with Spot. I've heard rumours that Mail-Manager chokes on this
abuse of the MSGID kludge, which I personally don't blame them.
@endnode

##---------------------------------------------------------------------
@node Q12 "Troubleshooting / Frequently asked questions"

Yes, it should work with AmiTCP. However you do need a bit of twisting.

First you should use get hold of the archive "IU-14-amitcp.lha" by
Michael B. Smith. Available from Aminet. Set it up. I also use
NNTPGet and PutMail. Thus I only use the Internet utils NNTPPost.

I included my config files for AmiTCP in the SampleCfg_AmiTCP directory
as well as the end of my Startnet and Stopnet scripts.

If you want to use NNTPxfer instead of NNTPGet you'll have to do:

 1> SetEnv NNTPRNews AmiGate GATENEWS

See the manual for NNTPxfer for an explanation of NNTPRNews.

I am not going to describe in details how to set up AmiGate for use with 
AmiTCP but you should set @{" PACKETAPPEND " LINK PACKETAPPEND} and have a look at the 
@{" DELETENEWSFROMUS " LINK DELETENEWSFROMUS} keyword.
@endnode

